Author: Marike Schwickardi
Subject: Manual injection scan_analog with very high charge
Text:
We just tried to inject everything we can (VL:3, VH:253, deltaV: 250) or a bit less (deltaV: 200). This corresponds to ~2500 and ~2000 electrons respectively.

we injected with scan_analog.py and analyzed it with the same script used to get plots shown in elog entry 441 (run 484).
It is the same chip with the same register configuration.

We see that the ToT value is not reaching more than about 10.

We also tried to inject just one pixel at once, it did not change the behaviour.

Author: Yannik Buch
Subject: Operating CPPM chip at low bias voltages
Text:
Interesting observation:

When lowering the PSUB/PWELL Voltage, the efficiency drops slightly but not very much up to 0.75 V.
At 0.625 V, we do not see any hits. Wen operating at 0.688V, we see hits first (quite many, analysis is pending) but at some point in time, the chips just stops sending data at all (zero hits).

This looks very much like the chip freezes, I don't think this is a drift effect because the edge from many hits per event to zero is from one moment to the other.

We did observe that the chip stops sending data when the registers are set completely wrong, and needs a power cycle to send data again (some digital thing appearently) so it might be the same here

Author: Benjamin Schwenker
Subject: Compare Corry and TBSW on Psub/Pwell can on Goe DUT
Text:
Comparison of efficiency and residuals rms and charge (ToT in LSB) mean for two frameworks (corryvrekan and tbsw) as cross check. 

https://github.com/BenjaminSchwenker/tbsw   (developed before corryvrekan and fully independent of it, originally based on ILCSoft)


The alignment and residuals in tbsw are slightly better. The efficiency comes out very much the same (few permill lower in tbsw). we should scan Psub/Pwell in smaller steps between 1.8 and 2.0
(either thursday or friday)

Refer to MIMOSA DAQ GOES TO SHIT Manual on green paper to fix it (also attached).

Text:
Here optimized values for the Normal Cascode frontend. It will be required to disable the Normal FE as it will overshoot a lot with these settings.

The threshold is about 350e, which is not great but much better than before.

Still, this is already at the border of stability.

Tests were run with the CPPM mosule (W5R18)

Author: Yannik Buch
Subject: Efficiency of small colliamtor vs wide collimator
Text:
After running 1h on the normal FE with the small and wide collimator to compare efficiencies we observed a difference of O(10%) in the efficiencies. Wide coll: 0.8996 Small coll: 0.9921.
On the basis of these findings we will continue measuring with the small collimator.
An assortment of plots is attached.

Author: Bernhard Pilsl
Subject: FIFO data format documentation
Text:
The FIFO data format from the FPGA is implemented in the following way:

this is actual hit data of the different hit pixel

the smallest possible frame consists only of 1 Hit,
spread over 2 data words,
and looks like this:

H | SOF| D0 | D1
H | D2 | D3 | EOF

H .. Header: 5bit
dx .. different (pixel index, te, le) data: 9 bit
SOF .. Start of frame
EOF .. End of frame

There might be more than 1 hit per frame,
so the Dx might occur n times.
In this case the last (possibly) not full 32 bit word
 will be filled with an idle block

There might also be triggerwords everywhere in the FIFO (distinguishable by 5 bit header)


The full event building procedure can be found in the source-file attached (part of custom EUDAQ build, important function is "Converting" )

Author: Marike Schwickardi
Subject: Efficiency analysis "fix"
Text:
We managed to get the efficiency from ~75% -> 99.3384(+0.0351626 -0.0370685)%
by changing the logic of the eudaq-event building in the monopix2-producer in the following way:

D ... data word, Tx ... Trigger word, |<-x->| ... EUDAQ event with trigger number x

*VARIANT_old:

	 Data from FIFO eg:
	 D D D T0 D D D D T1 D D D D D T2 D D D T3 D D D D
	       |<---0--->||<----1---->||<--2-->||<-------... (store for next execution)
 
 *VARIANT_new:
	  D D D T0 D D D D T1 D D D D D T2 D D D T3 D D D D
		|<----------0---------->|
		           |<--------1--------->|
		                        |<---------------------... next execution ...

So basically we assign each hit to 2 triggerNumbers.


ADDITIONALLY the triggerNumber of the monopix2 had to be shifted by +1 relative to the telescope planes (done offline in Corryvreckan)
This might be due to a static offset in the setup (eg. starting to count at 0 or 1)...


Author: Bernhard

Author: Benjamin Schwenker
Subject: Efficiency inhomogeneity and triggerid-offset efficiency
Text:
run no    trigger rate    efficiency     eff. with triggerid-offset
228         300 Hz          75%             26%
232         600 Hz          75%             26% 
233         100 Hz          75%             27%
235         1.5 kHz         68%             30%

the efficiency is only to compare the measurements, not to be used as absolute value


Run The trigger-id offset efficiency is the efficiency of the monopix when sending hits after the next trigger word. with the triggers shifted by one in respect to the trigger of the telescope. Therefore this should be zero, but is nonzero as some events of the monopix are late and therefore associated to the proceeding trigger id.

Author: Marike Schwickardi
Subject: Efficiency analysis observations
Text:
We are seeing pixel efficiencies we'd not expect.
In Run071 we analyzed an overnight run O(10^7) events (good statistics)
  -  in the region of column ~190 we get efficiencies of up to 95% with little fluctuations
  -  in the upper columns there are also pixel with high efficiencies, but there's more "noise"
  - in between clearly a gradient appears
  - looking at the hitmap this behaviour doesn't seem to be related to the beam spot

To investigate this further we reduced the "effective trigger-rate" by enlargening the TLU-veto from the BDAQ-board

In Run087 a trigger-veto of 60000 * 25ns ~ 1500 us is applied (rate reduced from 1.6 kHz -> 300 Hz)
  - the previously seen gradient is no longer observed
  - the regions with a high homogeneous efficiency are also no longer observed (this might be related to worse statistics)


Summary:
* Beam Spot does not seem to influence efficiency-maps
* Beam Rate clearly does influence the efficiency-maps

The "lost efficiency" might be due to the not ideal association of TJMonopix2 data to TLU triggerNmbs.

When (during analysis) shifting the triggerNmbs of the Monopix by +1 we still get some (much less than without a shift) valid tracks and efficiency maps with an "inversed" gradient.

Author: Christian Irmler
Subject: Grounding scheme
Text:
Grounding scheme of setup in TB22

The TJ-MP2 setup is floating wrt. the telescope. 
The telescope itself and its frame are isolated from the "DESY table" and thus floating wrt. to earth. No information about grounding scheme 
of telescope readout.

All channels of the used HAMEG power supply are floating and thus isolated to each other.
Ch2-4 are used for the TJ-MP2 board. On the TJMP2 board all GNDs are connected, but isolated from earth (chassis GND).
The bdaq53 board is powered by ch1 of the same HAMEG.
The TLU chassis is connected to earth. The TLU is connected with the bdaq53 by a custom cable. This cable unfortunately connects GND with 
chassis GND (earth).
This connection could be problematic --> can be resolved by using on of the RJ45 to HDMI converter boards.
